<F P=101> KAZAKHSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Cholera Cases in Almaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1409113693 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1057 GMT 14 Sep 93 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1409113693 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Following item transmitted via KYODO] </F>
  [Text] Almaty, Kazakhstan, has not declared a state of 
emergency following the appearance of cholera cases in the city. 
All market places were opened on Tuesday [14 September]. Only 
the street trade in pies and beverages is banned. 
  However, the quarantine introduced on Monday has not been 
lifted. Lessons in schools have been interrupted until Friday, 
but day care centers continue to function. 
  According to the civil aviation department, charter flights 
have been stopped to Pakistan, Afghanistan, Iran, Turkey, India, 
and the United Arab Emirates, as well as to Uzbekistan, 
Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, and South Kazakhstan. There have been 
no restrictions in other directions. 
  The acting chief of the city epidemiological service, 
Aleksandr Kim, announced that the 152 passengers who arrived by 
plane from Karachi, Pakistan last Thursday were isolated as 
suspected cholera patients. They are in satisfactory condition. 
  The chief of the sanitation service of the city, Anuar 
Talkimbayev, reports there are 16 cholera patients in 
Kazakhstan, 8 of them in the capital. Treatment is active and 
there is no reason to fear for the lives of the patients. 
  However, experts from the Kazakh anti-plague center claim 
that the type of cholera brought from Pakistan differs from the 
classical form and is difficult to treat by conventional means. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

