<H3> <TI>   Rapid Increase in AIDS Among Women Seen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  93WE0573A London THE TIMES in English 17 Aug 93 p 4 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 93WE0573A </F>
<F P=104>  London THE TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article: "Women Face Greater Increase of AIDS"] </F>
  [Text] AIDS in Britain is growing more rapidly among women, 
figures from the public Health Laboratory Service show (Nigel 
Hawkes writes). In the 12-month period ending July 1993, there 
were 171 new cases among women, an increase of 22 percent over 
the previous year. Among men, 1,408 new cases were recorded, a 
rise of only 8 percent. 
  The figures do not, however, suggest that an epidemic of 
heterosexual AIDS is yet under way. Only nine women are recorded 
as having caught AIDS from a partner in the UK outside the 
high-risk groups, against ten in the previous 12 months. The 
great majority of sexually transmitted cases were caught from 
partners abroad (76) or by drug users sharing needles (32). The 
total of AIDS cases in the UK since reporting began in 1982 has 
reached 7,842 (7,264 male and 578 female), of whom 4,893 have 
died. 

</TEXT>

