<H3> <TI>   Meningitis Outbreak at Hampshire University </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WE0116A London THE GUARDIAN in English 3 Dec 93 p 11 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WE0116A </F>
<F P=104>  London THE GUARDIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article: "Woman Critical After Outbreak of Meningitis"] </F>
  [Text] A woman student, aged 19, was critically ill in 
hospital yesterday amid what health officials described as an 
"unexpected increase" in bacterial meningitis among students in 
Southampton, Hampshire. 
  Two other students -- men aged 18 and 20 -- are being 
treated 
for the disease which can be passed on by close contact such as 
kissing or by sharing a glass. 
  Doctors have reported eight cases of meningococcal 
meningitis 
and septicaemia since the beginning of October instead of the 
normal two to four cases for the time of the year. 
  Of the eight, three are students at Southhampton Institute 
of 
Higher Education and two at Southhampton University. 
  Two further cases involved a young girl and a baby, and the 
eighth case was brought in from outside the area. 
  A spokeswoman for Southampton University Hospitals' Trust 
said two of the five students were now well. 
  Of the other three students both the men were improving, but 
the 19-year-old woman was "critical" in intensive care. None of 
the other cases was said to be in any danger. 

</TEXT>

