Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by David Brindle, social services correspondent: </F>
"Hospital Waiting Lists Go Through 1 Million Barrier, Ministers 
Admit"] 
  [Text] The Government last night acknowledged that more 
than a million people in England are waiting for hospital 
treatment. 
  Provisional figures issued by the Department of Health show 
a 
record 1,017,763 patients awaiting admission at the end of June, 
compared with 994,974 at the end of March. 
  The figures also show an increase between March and June of 
15.6 percent in patients waiting more than a year -- a slightly 
bigger rise than that in Labour's unofficial count published on 
Monday. 
  Labour estimated that the total waiting list had passed a 
million, based on an unofficial tally for the end of April. But 
until last night neither the department nor ministers had 
admitted that the psychologically important barrier had been 
breached for the first time. 
  The official figures for June show the same totals for the 
14 
English health regions, as Labour had collected, but show 11,930 
people, compared with Labour's 10,429, waiting for treatment at 
the specialist hospitals run as special health authorities. This 
includes 275 patients waiting more than two years, despite 
Patient's Charter commitment that nobody should face this delay. 

