<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turks, Romanians Discuss Joint Health Projects </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201081294 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1914 GMT 11 Jan 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1201081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 11/01/1994 -- A string of 
projects stipulated in the additional protocol of cooperation in 
health care between Romania and Turkey was outlined to Premier 
Nicolae Vacaroiu by Turkish Health Minister Kazim Dinc during 
the interview at Victoria Palace, on January 11. 
  It is about projects of cooperation in medicine industry and 
cooperation in third markets in this branch, exchanges of 
specialists and experience on intensive care as well as in 
geriatrics and gerontology. The guest also signed in this 
respect the founding act of a branch in Turkey of the Romanian 
Institute "Dr. Ana Aslan," under the aegis of the Turkish Health 
Ministry. 
  Appreciating the additional protocol under negotiation, 
Premier Nicolae Vacaroiu stressed the Romanian Government's 
interest in the development of the bilateral relations with 
traditional partners and especially with Turkey, insisting on 
the future prospects of these relations. 
  At the close of the meeting, Premier Vacaroiu asked the 
guest 
to convey to the Turkish prime minister the invitation to visit 
Bucharest. 
  "I consider the interviews we have had in Romania as very 
useful for both parties," Turkish Health Minister Kazim Dinc 
told the press after his interview with Romanian Premier Nicolae 
Vacaroiu. The Turkish minister referred then to the protocol 
concerning the health field signed in 1991, to the goals of his 
visit, to the ways of developing the health sector, altogether 
subjects discussed during his interview with the Romanian health 
minister, Professor Doctor Iulian Mincu. 
  "We, the Government of Turkey, wish to employ Romania's 
experience in geriatrics and gerontology," said the Turkish 
minister and added that Turkish doctors would come to Romania 
for specialization stages in order to become trainers for 
specialists in the field once they get back to Turkey. 
  An important sector for the development of the 
Romanian-Turkish cooperation is the medicine industry, said 
Minister Dinc, who has remarkably expressed in all his 
statements Turkey's willingness to stand by Romania for the 
better of the worse. 

</TEXT>

