<F P=101> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scientists Test Drug on HIV-Positive Patients </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2501091194 Sofia BTA in English 2146 GMT 24 Jan 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2501091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, January 24 (BTA) -- Factor-R, a Bulgarian 
preparation stimulating the immune system, will be tested on 
HIV- positive Bulgarians. The National Institute of Medical 
Preparations endorsed the clinical testing today. 
  It is up to HIV-carriers and persons who have developed the 
full symptoms of AIDS to decide whether to accept the proposal 
for taking part in the clinical tests of Factor-R which will be 
carried out in Bulgaria for the first time. 
  Factor-R has been developed by a medical team headed by 
Prof. 
Bogdan Petrunov, director of the National Centre of Infectious 
and Parasitic Diseases. The team has been working jointly with 
Life Choice International and the Applied Research Combine of 
Pharmaceutics. The tests of the preparation began in October 
last year. It is tested on a voluntary basis in the United 
States, being administered to subjects from Austin, Texas. The 
blood tests of the patient who was the first to start taking 
Factor-R show a definite improvement, BTA was told by Life 
Choice International. 

</TEXT>

