<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Statistics Show 170 People Tested HIV-Positive in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101074494 Prague CTK in English 1837 GMT 20 Jan 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2101074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 20 (CTK) -- In 1993, a total of 
3,409,610 people in the Czech Republic were tested for HIV, the 
virus that causes AIDS, with 170 testing positive. Of these, 45 
have developed AIDS, according to Ministry of Health 
information, ministry spokeswoman Marketa Soukupova told CTK 
today. 
  Of those who tested HIV-positive, 150 were men and 20 were 
women. Of those stricken with AIDS, 41 were men and 4 were women. 
  The highest-risk groups were made up of recipients of blood 
and blood products (14 HIV-positive and 3 with AIDS) and 
hemophiliacs (16 HIV-positive and 1 with AIDS). 
  The highest percentage of HIV carriers and AIDS sufferers 
was 
found among homosexuals and bisexuals (16 HIV-positive and 7 
with AIDS). Prague had the highest total of HIV carriers, with 
110 people in various stages of the disease. 
  A large portion of HIV carriers in the Czech Republic is 
made 
up of foreign students and workers, of whom 84 tested 
HIV-positive and one developed AIDS. 
  Thirty-three of the 170 who tested HIV-positive died in 
1993. 

</TEXT>

