<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fifteen Percent Drop in New AIDS Carriers in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0301115094 Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in Hebrew 3 Jan 94 p 20 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA0301115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv MA'ARIV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yisra'ela Shaqed] </F>
  [Text] Some 169 new AIDS carriers were uncovered among 
115,000 people tested in 1993, compared with 201 carriers 
uncovered among 80,000 people tested in 1992. This was 
announced by Dr. Tzvi Ben- Yishay, chairman of the Health 
Ministry's supreme committee on AIDS prevention. 
  The findings point to a 15 percent drop in the number of new 
carriers in 1993 and to a rise in the number of female carriers, 
who now constitute 36 percent of the carriers, compared to 30 
percent in 1992. 
  To date, 278 Israelis have contracted the disease. Of these, 
198 died and 15 left the country. The number of known carriers 
is 1,102, but the Health Ministry estimates their number at 
2,500. 

</TEXT>

