<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Official Says Kiev, Vilnius Not Reporting Accidents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901215694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1939 GMT 19 Jan 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1901215694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The disruption of connections between the nuclear 
supervision services of Russia, Ukraine and Lithuania may lead 
to the most undesirable effects in the sphere of radiation and 
nuclear safety, the head of the press office of the Russian 
Goskomatomnadzor (state committee for supervising nuclear 
installations), Yuriy Rogozhin, told INTERFAX today. 
  Rogozhin said his committee's leadership knew of the 
accident 
at the 4th reactor of the Zaporozhskaya nuclear power station in 
Ukraine on January 12 only five days later from a fax from the 
European Nuclear Society HQ in Switzerland to Moscow. 
  Rogozhin said Russia received information on the accident on 
the Ignalina nuclear power station in Lithuania only from the 
press. 
  He pointed out that failures to provide the necessary 
information to the Russian Goskomatomnadzor by former Soviet 
republics run counter to the official agreement between the 
nuclear supervision organizations which was reached shortly 
after the break-up of the Soviet Union. 
  According to Rogozhin, the Ignalina nuclear power station 
was 
equipped with reactors of type RBMK-1500, which are identical to 
those that were installed in Chernobyl. With the lack of 
information, it is difficult to speak of the maintenance of 
nuclear safety. 
  Rogozhin pointed to the fact that reactors functioning now 
in 
former Soviet republics are made in Russia, and Moscow must be 
fully informed of even the most insignificant accidents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

