<H3> <TI>   Conflict Growing Between Kravchuk, Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801135394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1148 GMT 18 Jan 94 
-- FOR OFFICAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1801135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On January 20, the Ukrainian parliament will gather 
for a session to evaluate the moves by President Kravchuk, who 
signed the document on Ukraine's nuclear disarmament, member of 
the Ukrainian parliament's Presidium and a leader of the Popular 
Rukh, Les Tanyuk, told INTERFAX-Ukraine. 
  Tanyuk announced that according to his sources, "Kravchuk is 
planning a big conflict with the parliament. The parliament may 
be dissolved," he said. He believes that in such a situation 
new parliamentary elections may not be held. 
  Ukraine signed the Moscow agreement "on its knees," said 
Tanyuk. This agreement cannot be implemented because Kravchuk is 
only planning to ask experts to make corresponding estimates. 
Tanyuk described such actions as "anti-state," and carried out 
under the pressure of forces which are not interested in 
Ukraine's development. 

