<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   India To Receive Extra Cryogenic Boosters for SLV-3 Rocket From Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012121293 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1135 GMT 30 Dec 93 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3012121293 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia pledges to supply to India at least four more 
cryogenic boosters for a SLV-3 rocket, twice more than 
stipulated by the 1991 contract. 
  As the General Director of Russia's Space Agency Yuriy 
Koptev 
has told INTERFAX, an agreement on additional supplies has been 
reached at negotiations in Bangalore between Indian Space 
Research Organization (ISRO) officials and Russian experts 
earlier this month. 
  In Koptev's words, India will get two more boosters as 
compensation for Russia's forced repeal of the additional 
agreements as incompatible with the Missile Technology Control 
Regime (MTCR), accords that provide for the delivery of 
cryogenic technology and equipment to Delhi and for Indian 
specialists' training. 
  Thereby, Koptev said, "Russia has kept virtually intact the 
volume of financing" envisaged by the contract and its addenda 
and estimated at $220 Mn. The first booster is to be supplied 
in 1995. 
  In Koptev's opinion, putting relations with ISRO on a 
footing 
in line MTCR, which Russia intends to join, has not had any 
adverse effect on bilateral cooperation, which is borne out by 
the two countries short-term plan to sign an intergovernmental 
agreement in the field. 

</TEXT>

