<H3> <TI>   WEU Assembly Encourages Cooperation With CIS in High-Tech </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0712145793 Brussels EUROPE in English 4 Dec 93 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0712145793 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "EC: WEU Assembly in Favour of </F>
Cooperation With CIS in High-Tech"; as released by Brussels 
Textline database] 
  [Text] Paris, 3 Dec 1993 (AGENCE EUROPE) - The Assembly of 
the Western European Union (WEU) adopted a recommendation in 
Paris urging the WEU Council to encourage cooperation with the 
countries of the former USSR in the field of high-tech, "so as 
to encourage transparency in the transfer of material for both 
civil and military use." Indeed, the Assembly notes that the 
internal stability in these countries depends to a large extent 
on modernising their structures and transformation in economic, 
industrial and technological domains, domains where it believes 
it is possible and desirable to improve Western assistance for 
these countries. The Assembly insists on the creation of a 
European information system, as currently initiatives often have 
a double use, and calls on WEU member countries to give all 
their political and economic support to Moscow's International 
Centre for Science and Technology, whose aim is to prevent the 
proliferation of technologies of mass destruction. Noting that 
Ukraine and Kazakhstan had not yet acceded to the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty, the Assembly called on the WEU Council 
to try to obtain this accession. 

</TEXT>

